46
00:02:35,428 --> 00:02:38,610
the rewards, the weapons, and the perks that you get,

47
00:02:39,270 --> 00:02:42,693
but it also has a great impact on the characters' reactions,

48
00:02:42,973 --> 00:02:45,335
the game structure, through unique missions,

49
00:02:46,376 --> 00:02:47,316
and the ending of the game.

50
00:02:48,386 --> 00:02:50,727
So quick survey here, who in the audience

51
00:02:50,747 --> 00:02:52,267
have played Mafia III?

52
00:02:54,108 --> 00:02:54,448
Okay.

53
00:02:56,609 --> 00:02:58,190
So for those who haven't played the game,

54
00:02:58,490 --> 00:03:00,631
after you've unlocked all three on the bosses,

55
00:03:01,151 --> 00:03:02,331
the structure goes like this.

56
00:03:04,052 --> 00:03:07,933
First, you go after individual rackets run by the mob.

57
00:03:08,674 --> 00:03:10,294
For example, the construction rackets

58
00:03:10,494 --> 00:03:11,455
in the downtown district.

59
00:03:12,754 --> 00:03:14,375
After you've conquered a racket,

60
00:03:14,815 --> 00:03:16,976
you have to call one of your underbosses.

61
00:03:17,577 --> 00:03:21,260
They will each give you unique rewards.

62
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:25,442
After the call, men from the faction you have chosen

63
00:03:25,503 --> 00:03:28,405
populate the racket, which becomes a friendly location.

64
00:03:29,485 --> 00:03:33,628
For example, the Haitian faction, run by Cassandra.

65
00:03:35,079 --> 00:03:38,021
Note that this faction change is temporary.

66
00:03:38,702 --> 00:03:41,604
So the ender bosses agree to help you in the short term,

67
00:03:42,244 --> 00:03:45,487
but a racket is fully under control of a character

68
00:03:45,707 --> 00:03:48,049
only if the whole district was conquered

69
00:03:48,309 --> 00:03:48,949
and assigned to them.

70
00:03:49,450 --> 00:03:50,771
We'll come to that shortly.

71
00:03:52,412 --> 00:03:54,574
There are two rackets per district.

72
00:03:55,494 --> 00:03:57,856
You conquer the second racket in downtown,

73
00:03:58,296 --> 00:03:59,157
the blackmail market.

74
00:04:00,523 --> 00:04:02,624
And after the second racket is conquered,

75
00:04:02,904 --> 00:04:04,445
again you have to call one of the boss.

76
00:04:05,245 --> 00:04:08,107
You can choose to assign the second racket in the district

77
00:04:08,147 --> 00:04:11,208
to the same on the boss, although the rewards offered

78
00:04:11,508 --> 00:04:15,270
are a bit less interesting, or to choose another one.

79
00:04:17,130 --> 00:04:19,051
Conquering both rackets of a district

80
00:04:19,311 --> 00:04:22,292
unlocks a unique mission, in which you can take out

81
00:04:22,332 --> 00:04:25,434
the district boss, who reports directly to Sal Marcano,

82
00:04:26,054 --> 00:04:27,675
the mafia boss in New Bordeaux.

83
00:04:29,481 --> 00:04:32,064
Just after the mission, a complex dialogue sequence

84
00:04:32,144 --> 00:04:36,148
called sit down is triggered to permanently

85
00:04:36,268 --> 00:04:37,028
assign the district.

86
00:04:37,469 --> 00:04:39,471
All characters will try to convince you

87
00:04:39,951 --> 00:04:41,313
to give them the new territory,

88
00:04:42,033 --> 00:04:44,816
and they will have a reaction based on who you choose.

89
00:04:46,678 --> 00:04:49,501
So there are two possibilities coming in a sit down.

90
00:04:50,562 --> 00:04:53,144
First possibility, both rackets were secured

91
00:04:53,184 --> 00:04:54,065
by the same character.

92
00:04:55,401 --> 00:04:58,122
or you have split the district between two underbosses

93
00:04:58,723 --> 00:05:00,824
who each secured one racket.

94
00:05:02,345 --> 00:05:04,806
So the racket assignments through the telephone call

95
00:05:05,306 --> 00:05:08,488
is a sort of promise that you do to a character.

96
00:05:09,508 --> 00:05:11,930
And when you choose an underboss to run a district,

97
00:05:13,070 --> 00:05:16,532
the decision is final, and all rackets in the district

98
00:05:16,792 --> 00:05:18,573
are reassigned based on your decision.

99
00:05:19,714 --> 00:05:23,316
So I'm going to show you in-game what a sit-down looks like.

100
00:05:25,046 --> 00:05:29,650
In the situation you're going to see, you have conquered Downtown and it's the first

101
00:05:29,791 --> 00:05:36,517
district that you have taken down. Downtown is split between two characters. You call

102
00:05:36,597 --> 00:05:43,303
Vito to hold the first racket and you call Cassandra for the second one. Now pay attention

103
00:05:43,363 --> 00:05:43,944
to what they say.

104
00:05:52,621 --> 00:05:55,682
This is our first step toward breaking Markano and taking over the city.

105
00:05:56,342 --> 00:05:59,062
I hear what y'all got to say, but I decide who gets the turf.

106
00:05:59,342 --> 00:06:00,783
And in the end, my decision is final.

107
00:06:01,223 --> 00:06:02,223
Well, hear this, Lincoln.

108
00:06:02,903 --> 00:06:05,184
You can make any final decisions you wanna make.

109
00:06:05,924 --> 00:06:10,445
But splitting the action in one of these districts between my men and theirs ain't happening.

110
00:06:11,065 --> 00:06:12,265
This turf comes to me.

111
00:06:12,986 --> 00:06:14,226
White boys are your problem.

112
00:06:14,950 --> 00:06:20,331
Jesus, shut the fuck up. My guys aren't down there boozing with the neighbors or igniting some

113
00:06:20,351 --> 00:06:26,854
kind of race war. They're making money. For you. That's all that matters. So forget all this

114
00:06:26,874 --> 00:06:32,095
hippie bullshit and let's get to work. And don't let it change your mind lad. I can handle

115
00:06:32,135 --> 00:06:38,737
both rockets without any of the bitchin' these two got going on right now. So because

116
00:06:38,997 --> 00:06:43,479
both Cassandra and Vito hold one racket, they each expect the district to be theirs.

117
00:06:44,457 --> 00:06:47,598
Burke, on the other hand, is less aggressive about it.

118
00:06:48,439 --> 00:06:51,680
So here the decision is still completely open for the player.

119
00:06:51,861 --> 00:06:54,302
You can still choose any of the underbosses.

120
00:06:57,624 --> 00:06:59,825
So today I'm going to talk specifically about

121
00:06:59,985 --> 00:07:03,687
two main components of the system-driven dialogue work

122
00:07:03,807 --> 00:07:05,308
that we have performed on Mafia III.

123
00:07:06,388 --> 00:07:08,069
First, the loyalty system.

124
00:07:08,770 --> 00:07:09,930
Before the dialogue experience.

125
00:07:11,025 --> 00:07:12,906
We built a relationship system first,

126
00:07:13,146 --> 00:07:14,627
based on territory division.

127
00:07:16,047 --> 00:07:18,608
And I'm going also to talk about dialogue design,

128
00:07:19,268 --> 00:07:22,550
and specifically how we built a library of dialogues

129
00:07:22,610 --> 00:07:25,631
that would reflect the loyalty system in a meaningful way.

130
00:07:27,292 --> 00:07:30,693
Before we begin, small definition of system-driven dialogue.

131
00:07:31,653 --> 00:07:34,954
So for me, system-driven dialogue reflect the rules

132
00:07:35,035 --> 00:07:36,495
and status of a game system.

133
00:07:37,283 --> 00:07:39,304
conveying expectations, relationships,

134
00:07:39,984 --> 00:07:42,446
consequences, and history between characters.

135
00:07:43,967 --> 00:07:46,908
And all of that is being driven by a set of rules,

136
00:07:47,229 --> 00:07:51,391
states, modifiers, possible interactions, and choices.

137
00:07:53,512 --> 00:07:56,034
Some examples that use system-driven dialogues.

138
00:07:57,074 --> 00:08:00,036
The Civilization games with varying relationships

139
00:08:00,556 --> 00:08:03,938
with each AI rival.

140
00:08:05,349 --> 00:08:08,110
the football manager series, where you have to talk,

141
00:08:08,170 --> 00:08:10,451
motivate, and negotiate contracts with your players,

142
00:08:11,811 --> 00:08:14,852
and The Sims, even though they use an abstract language

143
00:08:14,992 --> 00:08:16,772
to convey moods and emotions.

144
00:08:18,933 --> 00:08:22,594
So in games, these types of dialogue are only reflected by,

145
00:08:23,514 --> 00:08:26,315
usually only reflected by a limited amount of lines,

146
00:08:27,035 --> 00:08:30,396
sometimes with voiceover, but usually only with text.

147
00:08:31,998 --> 00:08:35,962
In Mafia 3, we built a big library of voiceover dialogues

148
00:08:36,022 --> 00:08:38,245
driven by a complex state of rules.

149
00:08:39,046 --> 00:08:42,890
And Sit Downs is our attempt to explore emotional

150
00:08:43,090 --> 00:08:45,513
and gameplay depth in system-driven dialogues.

151
00:08:47,395 --> 00:08:50,058
So before we start here, I want to present you

152
00:08:50,098 --> 00:08:51,259
the development timeline.

153
00:08:52,177 --> 00:08:54,418
and decisions exactly how they happened,

154
00:08:54,758 --> 00:08:56,939
but rather they are shown easier to digest.

155
00:08:58,019 --> 00:09:00,540
The reality is a bit more granular than what I present.

156
00:09:01,221 --> 00:09:03,622
I know I have some colleagues in the audience.

157
00:09:04,002 --> 00:09:05,262
Please don't call me a liar.

158
00:09:06,863 --> 00:09:09,084
Or at least wait until the end of the presentation.

159
00:09:11,245 --> 00:09:14,586
So my initial mission was to design the relationship system

160
00:09:14,946 --> 00:09:17,847
that would drive the logic behind all the choices

161
00:09:17,907 --> 00:09:19,388
and their consequences on characters

162
00:09:20,088 --> 00:09:20,848
and the game structure.

163
00:09:22,890 --> 00:09:25,931
I knew a few things, starting working on the loyalty system.

164
00:09:27,251 --> 00:09:30,312
There are three underbosses to choose to assign territory.

165
00:09:31,113 --> 00:09:33,454
Six open districts to assign in total.

166
00:09:34,514 --> 00:09:38,455
And two rackets to assign per district, so 12 in total.

167
00:09:40,576 --> 00:09:43,777
The rackets are assigned temporarily in the phone call

168
00:09:43,817 --> 00:09:45,438
and the final decision for the district

169
00:09:45,738 --> 00:09:47,939
in sit-down sequences takes priority.

170
00:09:49,779 --> 00:09:53,060
Based on the choices performed, up to two underbosses

171
00:09:53,180 --> 00:09:55,521
can decide to leave the crime operation completely,

172
00:09:56,281 --> 00:09:59,763
only leaving you with one underboss at the end of the game.

173
00:10:01,723 --> 00:10:04,444
The player can accomplish side activities

174
00:10:04,524 --> 00:10:07,345
for each character to improve the relationship with them.

175
00:10:09,006 --> 00:10:11,127
And the final result of the loyalty system

176
00:10:11,407 --> 00:10:14,828
influences the multiple endings of the game.

177
00:10:15,128 --> 00:10:17,369
So these were my design constraints.

178
00:10:18,962 --> 00:10:21,424
From these constraints, we set some creative goals

179
00:10:21,685 --> 00:10:22,185
for the future.

180
00:10:23,406 --> 00:10:25,808
We wanted first to design a real system

181
00:10:25,989 --> 00:10:28,811
behind these choices, not having anything scripted

182
00:10:29,392 --> 00:10:30,793
or forced or cheated.

183
00:10:32,755 --> 00:10:35,177
We wanted tension to escalate throughout the game.

184
00:10:36,458 --> 00:10:39,881
Actual consequences on the game structure and the economy.

185
00:10:40,562 --> 00:10:42,424
On the bosses being able to drop out

186
00:10:42,664 --> 00:10:44,906
of the operation was a good start.

187
00:10:47,173 --> 00:10:52,556
And we wanted dialogue delivery, animation, poses,

188
00:10:52,957 --> 00:10:55,838
and facial expression as the primary form

189
00:10:55,978 --> 00:10:57,279
of the system feedback loop.

190
00:10:57,660 --> 00:11:01,482
So we didn't want any relationship score, bar,

191
00:11:01,802 --> 00:11:03,603
or text to drive the experience.

192
00:11:03,964 --> 00:11:07,266
I wanted players to focus on dealing with egos

193
00:11:07,646 --> 00:11:09,127
and demanding personalities.

194
00:11:09,767 --> 00:11:12,429
And that was for me one of the most challenging goal.

195
00:11:14,269 --> 00:11:16,170
And then we wanted no dialogue game,

196
00:11:16,590 --> 00:11:18,291
as in interactive dialogue systems.

197
00:11:19,031 --> 00:11:21,072
All interactions with the loyalty system

198
00:11:21,472 --> 00:11:24,654
are based on territory division,

199
00:11:24,774 --> 00:11:26,655
so rackets and district assignments.

200
00:11:27,175 --> 00:11:28,896
And optionally, side activities.

201
00:11:30,657 --> 00:11:32,778
So keeping everybody happy would mean

202
00:11:32,918 --> 00:11:34,819
doing some compromises in terms of the

203
00:11:34,879 --> 00:11:36,699
short-term rewards that you would be getting.

204
00:11:38,380 --> 00:11:41,942
Each character would offer a different set of perks.

205
00:11:42,857 --> 00:11:44,298
appealing to different kinds of players.

206
00:11:46,720 --> 00:11:48,521
So these were my player-facing goal.

207
00:11:49,482 --> 00:11:53,665
I had also defined goals for the underbosses themselves.

208
00:11:53,865 --> 00:11:57,168
After all, I was designing a simple AI system,

209
00:11:57,868 --> 00:12:00,931
so I needed a direction to define the basic concepts

210
00:12:01,311 --> 00:12:03,252
that would drive their persona.

211
00:12:04,914 --> 00:12:08,596
So these AI concepts are reflected through modifiers.

212
00:12:10,652 --> 00:12:13,714
The first concept for the underbosses is greed.

213
00:12:15,836 --> 00:12:17,818
They get some points for gaining a racket.

214
00:12:18,799 --> 00:12:20,841
They get some points for gaining a district.

215
00:12:22,082 --> 00:12:24,344
They lose points for losing a racket.

216
00:12:26,626 --> 00:12:29,428
The second concept is impatience.

217
00:12:31,270 --> 00:12:33,351
Underbosses dislike being ignored,

218
00:12:33,912 --> 00:12:35,673
and when they are not chosen for a district,

219
00:12:35,894 --> 00:12:36,895
they lose points.

220
00:12:39,686 --> 00:12:42,187
Since there are three characters for each district

221
00:12:42,207 --> 00:12:45,209
to assign, there are more points to lose than to gain.

222
00:12:45,969 --> 00:12:47,350
And with this simple balance,

223
00:12:47,850 --> 00:12:50,031
escalating tension was achieved.

224
00:12:51,351 --> 00:12:55,553
So this can be overcome by making cautious racket

225
00:12:55,593 --> 00:12:58,014
and district choices and doing side activities

226
00:12:58,074 --> 00:12:59,235
for each character.

227
00:13:01,116 --> 00:13:04,117
And finally, characters didn't need to be aware

228
00:13:04,157 --> 00:13:07,299
of more things than what they were exposed to.

229
00:13:07,479 --> 00:13:09,000
So if I call an underboss.

230
00:13:10,913 --> 00:13:13,274
to secure a racket that won't make

231
00:13:13,314 --> 00:13:14,995
the other characters upset.

232
00:13:15,315 --> 00:13:17,436
They don't even know they haven't been caught.

233
00:13:18,457 --> 00:13:21,919
So these AI concepts are rather simple and natural.

234
00:13:22,159 --> 00:13:25,080
I don't need a lot of explanation done in game

235
00:13:25,140 --> 00:13:27,642
for the player to understand these rules.

236
00:13:29,483 --> 00:13:30,463
So I knew my modifiers.

237
00:13:31,064 --> 00:13:33,985
Now I needed to define the different states

238
00:13:34,266 --> 00:13:35,766
influenced by these modifiers.

239
00:13:36,960 --> 00:13:39,102
I started with the base states

240
00:13:39,342 --> 00:13:41,304
that are purely modifier driven.

241
00:13:41,744 --> 00:13:43,646
Imagine a zero to a hundred scale.

242
00:13:45,448 --> 00:13:49,872
And these states were content, neutral, and angry.

243
00:13:50,733 --> 00:13:52,355
So these would be the states of the characters

244
00:13:52,415 --> 00:13:53,556
for a majority of the time.

245
00:13:54,217 --> 00:13:56,239
Underbosses start neutral.

246
00:13:58,221 --> 00:14:00,483
Then we have what we call overwrite states.

247
00:14:02,022 --> 00:14:04,427
These are influenced by modifiers,

248
00:14:04,828 --> 00:14:06,551
but can ignore the usual logic

249
00:14:08,154 --> 00:14:09,857
by having some specific rules.

250
00:14:10,859 --> 00:14:13,784
The first override state is ultimatum.

251
00:14:15,910 --> 00:14:18,611
It's triggered as a sort of last chance

252
00:14:18,771 --> 00:14:21,812
to make this right with a character who had enough.

253
00:14:22,813 --> 00:14:25,074
It was introduced to make sure that the tension escalation

254
00:14:25,154 --> 00:14:28,935
was not too extreme, and only one character

255
00:14:28,995 --> 00:14:31,976
can reach the ultimatum states throughout the whole game.

256
00:14:33,977 --> 00:14:36,138
When things are really bad with a character,

257
00:14:36,558 --> 00:14:38,038
the worst state is triggered.

258
00:14:39,303 --> 00:14:40,984
