00:17:06,606 --> 00:17:08,968
The player can see the rewards and penalties

306
00:17:09,008 --> 00:17:11,110
for each character, and they say something

307
00:17:11,270 --> 00:17:12,531
each time you highlight them.

308
00:17:13,491 --> 00:17:18,215
Here focus on Vito and his rewards, Burke and Cassandra.

309
00:17:19,690 --> 00:17:22,171
After you've selected a character to run the district,

310
00:17:22,511 --> 00:17:24,212
Lincoln announces the decision.

311
00:17:26,054 --> 00:17:28,195
Each character reacts back to back.

312
00:17:29,276 --> 00:17:33,038
First reaction, second, and third reaction.

313
00:17:34,279 --> 00:17:36,860
And finally, Lincoln sends everyone home.

314
00:17:39,042 --> 00:17:42,744
So as a recap, you can see the skeleton of a sit-down here.

315
00:17:43,861 --> 00:17:46,344
Sometimes we break these rules when we have big,

316
00:17:46,764 --> 00:17:50,248
special moments, like a character going into an ultimatum

317
00:17:50,328 --> 00:17:52,590
or wild state, but this is how it works

318
00:17:53,511 --> 00:17:55,133
for the majority of sit-downs.

319
00:17:58,255 --> 00:18:00,636
So now we need to define how we would approach

320
00:18:01,256 --> 00:18:01,976
dialogue scoping.

321
00:18:02,297 --> 00:18:05,237
In the prototype, we had simple design text

322
00:18:05,518 --> 00:18:08,919
with variables and conditions inside the text.

323
00:18:09,139 --> 00:18:13,640
So for example, I have two rackets and I am content.

324
00:18:14,920 --> 00:18:17,901
But I didn't know how these variables would translate

325
00:18:18,141 --> 00:18:20,362
when we would scope the actual dialogue lines.

326
00:18:21,928 --> 00:18:24,150
So through the dialogues, we needed to convey

327
00:18:24,210 --> 00:18:25,731
three pieces of information.

328
00:18:26,451 --> 00:18:29,654
It was important for the dialogue to first serve

329
00:18:30,154 --> 00:18:30,615
the system.

330
00:18:32,276 --> 00:18:34,618
Dialogues needed to convey the loyalty states

331
00:18:34,838 --> 00:18:38,301
of the on the bus, how many rackets this occurred

332
00:18:38,341 --> 00:18:40,442
in the district, two, one, or zero,

333
00:18:41,603 --> 00:18:45,006
and state transitions, positive and negative changes

334
00:18:45,326 --> 00:18:45,846
in the system.

335
00:18:48,075 --> 00:18:50,997
So there are interesting examples of actual viable

336
00:18:51,398 --> 00:18:53,079
audio design in sports commentaries,

337
00:18:53,400 --> 00:18:56,262
with announcers talking about game scores

338
00:18:56,322 --> 00:18:58,844
and statistics in a smooth and natural way,

339
00:18:59,385 --> 00:19:01,247
but it's very hard to produce well.

340
00:19:02,007 --> 00:19:04,249
And here, we were created of a narrative

341
00:19:04,289 --> 00:19:07,933
and emotional experience, not really talking about stats.

342
00:19:09,794 --> 00:19:12,317
So the resolution was clear, we would define

343
00:19:13,366 --> 00:19:15,727
individual dialogue assets, which would reflect

344
00:19:15,847 --> 00:19:18,528
the combination of the loyalty states,

345
00:19:19,108 --> 00:19:22,409
number of rackets held, and any other condition

346
00:19:23,169 --> 00:19:24,970
that the underbosses would react on.

347
00:19:25,510 --> 00:19:28,631
Then it would be all about the writing and the performance.

348
00:19:29,792 --> 00:19:31,633
We would need a lot of individual assets

349
00:19:31,833 --> 00:19:34,494
to support the game system, but we believed

350
00:19:34,554 --> 00:19:37,535
it was the right direction, sorry.

351
00:19:39,265 --> 00:19:41,787
We would also have to define a broad dialogue library

352
00:19:41,827 --> 00:19:45,550
that could survive designer iterations and create variety.

353
00:19:47,992 --> 00:19:51,275
And because we would have such a big amount of lines,

354
00:19:53,357 --> 00:19:55,739
thinking in branches would be unmanageable.

355
00:19:56,019 --> 00:19:57,641
So when I talk about branches,

356
00:19:58,321 --> 00:20:00,924
think interactive dialogue systems

357
00:20:01,004 --> 00:20:03,206
like Mass Effect or The Walking Dead.

358
00:20:04,627 --> 00:20:08,949
