359
00:20:09,329 --> 00:20:11,030
depending on the choices performed.

360
00:20:11,830 --> 00:20:13,851
Here, we would approach the dialogue design

361
00:20:13,891 --> 00:20:17,993
with a database mindset, rather than controlled branches.

362
00:20:20,134 --> 00:20:21,435
In addition to the loyalty states

363
00:20:21,975 --> 00:20:23,396
and number of racket secured,

364
00:20:24,076 --> 00:20:27,238
we needed additional direction for the dialogue scoping.

365
00:20:28,808 --> 00:20:31,489
The first direction is that all transitions

366
00:20:31,789 --> 00:20:34,371
from one dialogue to the other must sound smooth

367
00:20:34,711 --> 00:20:35,712
when played back to back.

368
00:20:36,392 --> 00:20:38,933
And there are many possible permutations.

369
00:20:40,714 --> 00:20:42,976
All the underbosses would talk individually,

370
00:20:43,036 --> 00:20:44,316
there's no group talk.

371
00:20:46,377 --> 00:20:49,779
And we would use talking positions for branches.

372
00:20:50,099 --> 00:20:52,921
So for pitches and reactions, if you remember,

373
00:20:54,822 --> 00:20:56,043
characters talk back to back.

374
00:20:57,245 --> 00:20:58,866
first, second, and third.

375
00:20:59,766 --> 00:21:03,167
Here, whether our characters talk first, second, or third,

376
00:21:04,107 --> 00:21:07,588
enables us to write the dialogue

377
00:21:07,708 --> 00:21:10,709
so characters bounces off of each other.

378
00:21:11,289 --> 00:21:14,450
And that makes the dialogue feel more alive.

379
00:21:15,311 --> 00:21:18,752
Branching dialogue has a set of advantages in the writing.

380
00:21:18,952 --> 00:21:21,472
It definitely feels more natural.

