00:42:13,693 --> 00:42:16,455
We track how many times it has been played in the game,

774
00:42:18,156 --> 00:42:20,998
when it was played last through a timestamp,

775
00:42:23,435 --> 00:42:25,977
And then we can define one option called play once,

776
00:42:26,397 --> 00:42:28,219
which enables us to discard a dialogue

777
00:42:28,739 --> 00:42:29,980
completely from the database

778
00:42:30,541 --> 00:42:32,702
when it was played once in the game.

779
00:42:34,964 --> 00:42:37,166
And finally, for each dialogue,

780
00:42:37,206 --> 00:42:40,048
there is one or more conditions defined.

781
00:42:40,649 --> 00:42:43,971
So conditions are logics based on game state variables.

782
00:42:44,392 --> 00:42:47,574
When we pass a dialogue, all linked conditions

783
00:42:47,835 --> 00:42:50,176
have to be true for the dialogue to be available.

784
00:42:52,072 --> 00:42:54,393
Let's take a look at what conditions are in sit down.

785
00:42:54,413 --> 00:42:59,335
So for example, conditions are the loyalty states.

786
00:42:59,655 --> 00:43:02,856
Content, neutral, angry, or ultimatum.

787
00:43:03,696 --> 00:43:07,218
If characters are war or was dead,

788
00:43:07,578 --> 00:43:09,519
they don't attend the sit down meeting.

789
00:43:11,480 --> 00:43:14,121
Then you have conditions related to the number of rackets

790
00:43:14,401 --> 00:43:17,202
secured in a district, two, one, zero.

791
00:43:19,537 --> 00:43:22,858
And then really any other additional variable.

792
00:43:23,159 --> 00:43:25,600
For example, it's the first district,

793
00:43:25,920 --> 00:43:27,181
it's the last district,

794
00:43:27,761 --> 00:43:30,923
Vito is the least powerful character in the city,

795
00:43:31,463 --> 00:43:33,124
the most powerful, et cetera.

796
00:43:36,066 --> 00:43:37,287
That's for dialogue data.

797
00:43:37,927 --> 00:43:41,169
Now let's go back to Vito's library of dialogues.

798
00:43:41,789 --> 00:43:44,491
Because there are so many, we need to organize them.

799
00:43:45,440 --> 00:43:47,321
So first, we put them in context.

800
00:43:47,842 --> 00:43:50,304
All greetings together, same for pitches,

801
00:43:50,904 --> 00:43:53,006
focus dialogues, and reactions.

802
00:43:54,988 --> 00:43:58,050
Then, inside categories, we define priorities.

803
00:43:58,831 --> 00:44:02,334
As many priority levels needed, depending on which dialogues

804
00:44:02,854 --> 00:44:04,596
are more important than others.

805
00:44:07,078 --> 00:44:08,879
For example, dialogues specific to the first

806
00:44:09,099 --> 00:44:12,202
or last sit down in the game are always marked

807
00:44:12,242 --> 00:44:13,203
as priority one.

808
00:44:14,819 --> 00:44:17,240
In priority two are dialogues related to characters

809
00:44:17,300 --> 00:44:19,541
being killed since the last sit down,

810
00:44:20,162 --> 00:44:23,303
reactions to an ultimatum states, et cetera.

811
00:44:25,044 --> 00:44:28,085
Then you really define as many priority levels as you need.

812
00:44:28,826 --> 00:44:31,567
And finally, your set of generic dialogues.

813
00:44:33,188 --> 00:44:34,829
Your really base design.

814
00:44:34,869 --> 00:44:37,270
They have less specific conditions,

815
00:44:37,670 --> 00:44:40,911
usually down to the loyalty states of the character.

816
00:44:43,295 --> 00:44:45,855
And so that's how we structure dialogue data

817
00:44:45,895 --> 00:44:47,736
for the other bosses in sit-downs.

818
00:44:48,416 --> 00:44:50,236
First, we organize by context.

819
00:44:51,056 --> 00:44:54,437
Then within context, we organize dialogue assets by priority.

820
00:44:55,197 --> 00:44:59,098
For example, here, greetings have three different levels

821
00:44:59,178 --> 00:44:59,938
of priority.

822
00:45:00,818 --> 00:45:02,859
Pitches have eight different levels.

823
00:45:04,599 --> 00:45:07,000
For each dialogue, we track a bunch of statistics

824
00:45:07,460 --> 00:45:10,800
and conditions on a mix of game state variables.

825
00:45:13,852 --> 00:45:16,375
So that was from the data structure.

826
00:45:17,256 --> 00:45:20,459
Now, when we detect that it's a character's turn to talk,

827
00:45:21,199 --> 00:45:24,062
we run a selection algorithm passing all dialogues

828
00:45:24,202 --> 00:45:28,026
from a context to choose the most relevant dialogue to play.

829
00:45:29,528 --> 00:45:31,650
First, we look at the play once status.

830
00:45:32,390 --> 00:45:34,472
If the play once option was ticked

831
00:45:34,873 --> 00:45:36,494
and the dialogue has been previously played,

832
00:45:37,035 --> 00:45:38,536
the dialogue is discarded.

833
00:45:40,366 --> 00:45:41,906
Then we look at the game state conditions

834
00:45:42,246 --> 00:45:43,286
linked with the dialogue.

835
00:45:43,707 --> 00:45:44,887
All conditions have to be met.

836
00:45:46,827 --> 00:45:49,248
If more than one dialogue returns true conditions,

837
00:45:49,888 --> 00:45:52,488
we compare different priority levels.

838
00:45:53,168 --> 00:45:54,188
If a priority dialogue,

839
00:45:55,249 --> 00:45:57,849
if a priority one dialogue is available,

840
00:45:58,629 --> 00:46:00,069
and another priority two,

841
00:46:00,169 --> 00:46:01,310
then we choose the priority one.

842
00:46:03,230 --> 00:46:04,910
If dialogues have the same priority level,

843
00:46:05,230 --> 00:46:07,551
then we compare the number of times they have been played.

844
00:46:08,398 --> 00:46:10,039
We pick the one which has been played

845
00:46:10,059 --> 00:46:11,380
the least amount of times.

846
00:46:12,900 --> 00:46:14,101
If there is still a tie,

847
00:46:14,301 --> 00:46:16,681
then we pick the least recently played dialogue.

848
00:46:19,422 --> 00:46:22,323
And finally, if there is still a tie,

849
00:46:22,564 --> 00:46:24,304
we pick a random dialogue from the group.

850
00:46:25,345 --> 00:46:28,186
The random part is interesting for me.

851
00:46:28,546 --> 00:46:32,287
In sit-downs, because of the enormous dialogue scope,

852
00:46:33,275 --> 00:46:35,737
most of the dialogues actually have never been played.

853
00:46:36,177 --> 00:46:38,899
And so, the algorithm, very often,

854
00:46:39,020 --> 00:46:41,982
has to pick randomly without a dialogue group.

855
00:46:42,762 --> 00:46:45,144
So it means that actually, as a designer,

856
00:46:45,404 --> 00:46:48,466
